data.content:
**MSTest Collection Assertions**

Your test works but produces poor failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest has dedicated collection and assertion APIs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, count)`** — on failure shows `"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"` instead of just `"IsTrue failed"`. Also makes `Count > 0` redundant.
- **`Assert.IsNotNull`** — clearer intent than `IsTrue(x != null)`.
- **Add message parameters** to `IsTrue` when a LINQ expression isn't self-evident from the failure output.

**Other options worth knowing:**

| Pattern | Use |
|---|---|
| `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` | Check membership |
| `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)` | Null checks |
| `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` | Same items, any order |
| `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)` | Subset check |

`CollectionAssert` works on `ICollection`, so you may need `.ToList()` if you have `IEnumerable`.
